name: Beadnell Bay
description:
The Bay can accommodate swells upto 12-15ft in size. Usually you choose the Bay due to its favorable wind directions and protected swell. The North end of the Bay needs a big (5ft+) south/south-easterly swell to work well. The middle of the Bay can produce excellent waves through most swell directions and sizes. The far south of the Bay is more open and holds big open northerly swells.

The Carrs reef in the midde of the Bay produces a left and a right that can hold swell upto 10ft easily and can result in quality 150 yard rides.

Always try and get the central to north end of the Bay on the pushing or high tide, the banks are better an the swell gets into the beach over the reefs more easily.

The Carrs reefs need a high tide to work and soon become exposed about an hour and a half after high.

It has a cleaner more sheltered and mellower wave at low tide from the end of the harbour jetty and is ideally suited to longboarders, the inside of the bay is excellent for beginners. It works on all stages of tide, but best a couple hours either side of low, tends to have a closing out beach break at high tide.North sea swell from NW through to E is best, but can have a wave on a strong S-SW channel swell. East winds are on shore. There are lifeguards on beach in summer, and there is a surf school and hire centre.

Any kind of onshore/cross shore wind wrecks the wave as there is no shelter. Transit time of swell from buoy(62105) to beach is 12-15hrs. Minimum conditions are 7ft and 7secs with glassy sea, if worse than this, save yourself a drive!

description:
Andicuri beach, is one of Aruba's number one surf spots. Mostly crowded by
bodyboarders it is a fun wedge type of wave. The wave is mostly a left
wedge but on big days the right jetty starts working. It's the most
consistent spot on the island with some nice hollow barrels and very fun
wedging ramps. It's for every level but on big days, experience is a must
because the wave gets very steep and throws really fast on the dry sand
bottom. Rides are generally short, but with good swell direction the side
waves get longer and connect better with the oncoming waves.

One of the better known spots on Aruba, both for bodyboarding and surfing, Dos
Playa is located on the north coast in the Natural Reserve Park Arikok and
is easily accessible. The name Dos Playa translates literally to "Two
Beaches" because there are two large bays separated by large cliffs. The
wave is a beach break that breaks really close to the shore. The waves
breaks left and right giving some of the most consistent surfing on the
island.This spot is prone to bigger swells and is really hollow and
powerful and offers big ramps and big barrels. On big days is not
recommended for beginners.

name: Druif
description:
Boca Druif, located behind the Tierra del Sol golf course, is a slab that doubles up on itself.
Strictly a bodyboarding wave but some surfers have been known to charge it
on the good offshore days. It breaks on a very shallow reef and is very
steep, hollow and powerful. The main peak is mostly lefts but because it is
a very wide bay it offers some rights. On the far right side of the bay
there is jetty that turns into a sick little right hander wedge. On average
onshore days the wave is still pretty hollow and barreling but with shorter
rides. This spot prefers a north swell with low or south winds in order
to really turn on with long, big and hollow lefts. This spot is for
experienced surfers only and is usually uncrowded.

name: Dunes/Dooms
description:
One of the most picturesque of surfing spots on Aruba. Rarely busy, even
on weekends, Dunes or Dooms as the locals call it, is a classic surfing
spot. Behind you is wide beach, with a rugged coastline, and rustic
lighthouse; in front of you the never ending blue. It breaks over shallow
reef and can hold very big waves. Swells can get up to 7 or 8 feet if your
lucky. This is the go-to spot on those elusive after-hurricane swells.
Dangerous though. There is no channel whatsoever so you have to paddle
straight out through the white water . Sea urchins, rips, undertow and
rocks rule the area. This spot is for your average surfer but on big days
experience is a must.

near the old Alto Vista Chapel on the north coast. It is mostly a left and

break in front of the rocky coast line.On good swell directions, waves
break both left and right, with good swells getting up to 5 or 6 feet. With
offshore winds, the waves turn on and are very hollow. The rocky coast line
provide some dangers because some waves break right in front of it. Don't
get caught inside.

name: Wariruri
description:
Wariruri is a bay located near the Bushiribana Goldmine Ruins on the
north coast of the island. A popular spot among surfers, Wariruri is a
place for all levels. Waves break both left and right and can reach faces
as high as six feet some times bigger. There are rocks on the left side and
far right side but other than that, it's a pretty good rippable wave with
good sections. On big days, the current can get strong and it can be
difficult to get out in to the line up. On the far left side of the bay,
there is a left peak which breaks on dry reef. Don't get caught on the left
side of the bay or you'll be into the rocks.

description: Located near Piriapolis.

name: Punta Negra
description: Located near Piriapolis.

name: Zorba
description: Beach break

name: Caracas
description: Right hand point break.

name: Nacho
description: Left hand point break. Breaks best from high to mid tide. Needs a Southerly swell.

name: Ahlestisheva
description: Right point break wave with stone bottom. With bridge from Vladivostok to Island Russian its easy access to spot.

name: Chernishova
description: Right and left stone bottom reef break. Close to the beach. With bridge from Vladivostok to Island Russian its easy access to spot.

name: Flotskiy
description: Beach break over sand and rock breaking left and right.

name: Halaktirskiy Beach
description: Deserted, well exposed beach break.

name: Hosta Rica
description: Stone bottom beach break with left and right waves. Access is really easy by beach in city Hosta. You can take train from Adler airport or from city Sochi.

name: Red Stones
description: Stone bottom reef break. Left and right wave. The left works better.\r\n\r\nWith big waves pretty dangerous shore break wave. To get there you can take ferry from Vladivostok to island Reyneke, then cross island and you find beach Red Stones. Wild and beautiful place.

name: Southern Cape, Anapa
description: About 20 minutes travel from the city centre. A rock bottom but not too shallow and a decent wave breaking left and right. Generally flat in the summer.

name: Chekka
description: A right off the jetty. It is only surfed a handful of times a year as it needs a big swell to wrap into the bay.

name: Colonel
description: This is a very fickle wave but when the winds are calm it has its moments

name: Edde Sands (Tum Tum Beach)
description: A standard beachbreak which can get epic a times if the banks are good. At other times its just a big closeout. Affected by southerly winds.

name: Pier and Friends
description: Average wave but has a bar right on the beach which kind of kind makes up for it. It\'s one of those mush-burger waves which is fat until it gets close to shore before dumping.

name: Ramlet al Bayhda
description: A beachbreak which can get pretty good. No-one surfs it much now because they opened up a sewer to the south and since most of the swell comes from a WSW angle and the wind pumps from a SW angle it gets quite dirty in the water.

name: Yours
description: This wave is a slab which breaks in very shallow water. Itâs a right hander that is intense and short but chucks the biggest pit.It\'s given this name as you\'ll not want to surf it alone and it kinda looks like ours from Sydney but on a smaller scale.\r\n

name: Agrili
description: Left point reef break. Swell angle will be important for wave size with more westerly swells larger.

name: Falasarna
description: Large reasonably consistent sand bottomed beach.

name: Fenekounta
description: Swell window is narrow between the islands and our forecast will be optimistic for this spot on SW swells.

name: Lygia
description: Relatively consistent beach and reef combination.

name: Makry Gialos
description: An easy paddle out from nearer the harbour with peaks along the beach. Surf on other beaches directly to the East too.

name: Methoni
description: Fickle point with a window for West to North West swells.

name: Petras
description: Consistent weak windswell in summer from the dominant meltemi wind pattern.

name: Stalida
description: Relatively consistent conditions  from the predominant onshore meltemi winds in summer but typically very small, shapeless wind swell due to the limited fetch.

name: Tinos
description: Consistent summer spot in the full fetch of the Meltemi wind.

name: Vouliagmeni
description: We don\'t have any details about Vouliagmeni at the moment.

name: Zagka
description: Beach break which can barrel if winds and swell align.

name: Zakros
description: Extremely inconsistent spot with this whole coast shadowed from the dominant westerly swells.

name: Karaburan
description: Various beach and reef breaks either side of the cape in the centre of the village.

name: Kemer
description: A number of spots from the 'artificial reef' of the ruins of the ancient city of Phaselis to the breaks in Sundance village.

name: Kilyos
description: Severals spots from sand bottom beach break suitable for all levels to a rock bottomed beach on the west of the cape more suitable for better surfers.

name: Olympos Beach
description: Large beach break suitable for all surfers and walking distance from the ruins of ancient Olympus

name: Rumeli Feneri
description: Shallow, rocky reef break offering good waves in the right conditions.

name: Suma Beach
description: Large sand bottomed beach suitable for all levels with a surf school and surf hire business.
